hands_on_practices.solution:
1. Start from the expansion

$$
\hat\Pi(q^2)
=\frac{2\alpha}{\pi}\int_0^1dx\,x(1-x)\ln\!\bigl(1-z\,x(1-x)\bigr),
\quad z=\frac{q^2}{m_e^2},
$$

and use

$$
\ln(1-a)=-\sum_{n=1}^\infty\frac{a^n}{n}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\hat\Pi(q^2)
=-\frac{2\alpha}{\pi}\sum_{n=1}^\infty\frac{z^n}{n}
\int_0^1dx\,[x(1-x)]^{n+1}.
$$

2. Define

$$
I_n=\int_0^1dx\,[x(1-x)]^{n+1}
=B(n+2,n+2)
=\frac{\Gamma(n+2)^2}{\Gamma(2n+4)}
=\frac{[(n+1)!]^2}{(2n+3)!}.
$$

Hence

$$
C_n=-\frac{2\alpha}{\pi}\frac{1}{n}I_n.
$$

3. The ratio is

$$
\frac{C_3}{C_2}
=\frac{\tfrac{-2\alpha}{\pi}\tfrac{1}{3}I_3}{\tfrac{-2\alpha}{\pi}\tfrac{1}{2}I_2}
=\frac{2}{3}\frac{I_3}{I_2}.
$$

4. Compute

$$
\frac{I_3}{I_2}
=\frac{[(3+1)!]^2/(2\cdot3+3)!}{[(2+1)!]^2/(2\cdot2+3)!}
=\frac{(4!)^2/9!}{(3!)^2/7!}
=\frac{576/362880}{36/5040}
=\frac{1/630}{1/140}
=\frac{2}{9}.
$$

Hence

$$
\frac{C_3}{C_2}
=\frac{2}{3}\cdot\frac{2}{9}
=\frac{4}{27}.
$$
